legal way to cross,
people are going to go across
illegally.

39:12.250 --> 39:16.321 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: One of the main
reasons why
Turkey has accepted this deal
permitting the

39:16.354 --> 39:21.626 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
return of migrants is that it
was promised
that its application to join the
European

39:21.659 --> 39:26.731 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Union will be fast-tracked. But
the terrorist
attacks in Brussels today have
damaged Turkey's

39:26.764 --> 39:28.600 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
cause.

39:28.633 --> 39:32.604 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Skeptical governments are
reluctant to accept
Turkey because it would extend
the European

39:32.637 --> 39:38.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
borders to Syria and Iraq, and
would possibly
increase the likelihood of
terrorism within

39:38.209 --> 39:42.947 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
the E.U. And so this
controversial arrangement
could be undermined.

39:42.981 --> 39:49.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These are hugely uncertain times
for the migrants
trapped in Greece and facing
deportation.

39:49.354 --> 39:55.960 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Malcolm Brabant
in Lesbos.

39:55.994 --> 40:09.807 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: It's a question of
when, not if,
a major seismic disaster will
strike the Pacific

40:09.841 --> 40:14.345 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Northwest. Scientists put the
odds of a big
earthquake and tsunami occurring
within the

40:14.379 --> 40:17.515 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
next 50 years at 37 percent.

40:17.548 --> 40:22.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, what are coastal communities
doing to
prepare and to make sure that
they are resilient

40:22.920 --> 40:25.056 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in the face of an extreme event?

40:25.089 --> 40:28.726 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
"NewsHour" correspondent William
Brangham
decided to find out.

40:28.760 --> 40:33.731 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: I'm standing
on the coast
of Washington. This is the very
edge of the

40:33.765 --> 40:38.036 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
continental United States. And
just a few
miles out in the Pacific Ocean
is considered

40:38.069 --> 40:42.473 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
one of the most dangerous
seismic faults in
all of North America.

40:42.507 --> 40:47.645 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Scientists believe if that fault
were to rupture,
it could devastate much of the
Pacific Northwest.

40:47.679 --> 40:52.483 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The fault is known as the
Cascadia subduction
zone, where two tectonic plates
meet underneath

40:52.517 --> 40:56.888 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Pacific Ocean. This fault
line stretches
700 miles along the coast.

40:56.921 --> 40:59.657 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KEN MURPHY, Federal Emergency
Management Agency:
Earthquakes have no season. It's
earthquake

40:59.691 --> 41:01.559 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
season every day.

41:01.592 --> 41:04.896 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Ken Murphy is
FEMA's regional
administrator. He oversees
emergency operations

41:04.929 --> 41:09.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for the Northwest region. He
says if this
whole fault were to rupture, not
only would

41:09.634 --> 41:14.439 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
there be a catastrophic
earthquake, but that
quake would then trigger an
enormous tsunami,

41:14.472 --> 41:17.375 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which would crash into the
Pacific Northwest
minutes later.

41:17.408 --> 41:24.549 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KEN MURPHY: You roughly have
about 140,000
square miles of communities and
land and people

41:24.582 --> 41:27.985 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
up and down Washington, Oregon,
and Northern
California.

41:28.019 --> 41:32.724 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Major cities
like Seattle,
Vancouver and Portland could be
seriously

41:32.757 --> 41:40.365 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
damaged. FEMA estimates that in
an 8- or 9-magnitude
quake, nearly 13,000 people
could be killed,

41:40.398 --> 41:44.569 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with another 20,000 injured. A
million people
would be made homeless.

41:44.602 --> 41:47.205 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And to some, these are
conservative estimates.

41:47.238 --> 41:53.611 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KEN MURPHY: It's not just FEMA,
but how we
as a nation are going to respond
to this,

41:53.644 --> 41:56.214 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
because it's really going to
take everybody's
efforts.

41:56.247 --> 42:01.085 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: This threat
has people across
the Northwest worried, no more
so than in

42:01.119 --> 42:07.091 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
coastal Washington, towns like
Westport, Ocean
Shores, Ocosta. Chuck Wallace is
an emergency

42:07.125 --> 42:08.860 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
manager for this county.

42:08.893 --> 42:10.661 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHUCK WALLACE, Grays Harbor
County Emergency
Manager: If you're in an
inundation zone or

42:10.695 --> 42:15.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
close to the coast, if you feel
an earthquake,
you have to suspect that a
tsunami could be

42:15.633 --> 42:19.971 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
following. And if there is one,
if they are
coming, we would have anywhere
from 15 to

42:20.004 --> 42:23.107 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
25 minutes along the coast to
move to higher
ground.

42:23.141 --> 42:27.612 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: And so the
town of Ocosta,
with just a few thousand
residents, is now

42:27.645 --> 42:33.351 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
building this, a large tsunami
evacuation
shelter here on top of its
public school.

42:33.384 --> 42:35.620 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's the first of its kind in
North America.

42:35.653 --> 42:37.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAULA AKERLUND, Superintendent,
Ocosta School
District: Well, right now we're
in the stair

42:37.488 --> 42:43.761 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
tower. This is after the
earthquake. We're
evacuating to the rooftop for
the tsunami

42:43.795 --> 42:45.029 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
evacuation.

42:45.062 --> 42:47.198 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So there's
four stairwells
like this one?

42:47.231 --> 42:49.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAULA AKERLUND: Yes.

42:49.066 --> 42:51.669 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Paula Akerlund
is the school
superintendent for the district,
and she was

42:51.702 --> 42:56.107 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
instrumental in getting this
shelter built.
Akerlund said they started
discussing this

42:56.140 --> 43:04.582 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
shelter four years ago. In an
ominous coincidence,
hours later, the massive tsunami
hit Japan.

43:04.615 --> 43:11.289 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The whole world watched as waves
destroyed
buildings and roads and entire
towns in just

